# Coherence Metrics

This document describes the primary coherence and phase-synchronization metrics used within the Fractal Resonance Processor (FPR) framework.

## 1. Global Order Parameter

The primary phase-synchronization metric is the Kuramoto order parameter:

`R = |(1/N) · Σ exp(i · φ_j)|`

where:

- `R → 1` indicates strong global phase coherence
- `R → 0` indicates incoherent or fragmented phase dynamics

This parameter is used to evaluate the degree of phase synchronization within interacting oscillator systems.

## 2. Coherence Accumulation

Within the FPR framework, coherence is treated as a dynamic accumulated property rather than a static state.

Coherence accumulation reflects the ability of the system to sustain stable phase relations over time under dissipative conditions.

## 3. Dynamic Stability Condition

The primary stability condition is:

`C(t) > P(t)`

where:

- `C(t)` represents accumulated coherence and regenerative phase-synchronization capacity
- `P(t)` represents dissipative losses and destabilizing extraction processes

Stable coherent retention becomes possible only when coherence accumulation exceeds total dissipative degradation over time.

## 4. Qualitative Characteristics of Phase Synchronization

The framework evaluates not only the numerical degree of synchronization, but also the qualitative characteristics of phase synchronization.

These include:

- phase drift direction
- phase-lock stability
- coherence retention duration
- fragmentation level
- fluctuation resistance
- convergence time
- stability of the coherent phase window

These characteristics determine whether a synchronized regime remains dynamically stable or degrades into dissipative fragmentation.

## 5. Resonance Compatibility

The framework assumes that synchronization efficiency depends on resonance compatibility between interacting phase structures.

Compatible phase interactions increase coherence accumulation, while incompatible interactions increase dissipative fragmentation.

## 6. Verification Objective

The purpose of these metrics is to provide measurable and reproducible indicators of:

- degree of phase synchronization
- qualitative characteristics of coherent phase interaction
- dynamic stability
- coherence retention
- resonance-driven convergence behavior within nonlinear interacting systems
